The physiological characteristics of children are mainly delicate Zang-Fu organs and underdeveloped physique and Qi.
Delicacy of Zang-Fu organs means that children's visceral functions are immature.
Underdevelopment of physique and Qi means children's body structure and physiological functions are incomplete.
Ancient physicians summarized children's physiology as underdeveloped Yin and Yang.
Children are often deficient in the lung, and the defensive exterior is weak.
Children are often deficient in the spleen, and transportation-transformation is not strong.
Children are often deficient in the kidneys, and kidney-Qi is not abundant.
Lung-Qi depends on the essence of the spleen for nourishment.
The spleen is the source for the generation of Qi and blood.
Original Yin and Yang in the kidneys are the root of life.
Constant abundance of the liver in children reflects vigorous Shaoyang growth activity.
Children's pathological features include easy onset and rapid transmission.
Delicate Zang-Fu organs make children susceptible to pathogenic factors.
Children's diseases transmit rapidly and often show susceptibility to deficiency and excess.
