Yin-Yang syndrome differentiation is the guiding principle for surgical syndrome differentiation.
Syndrome differentiation of surgical diseases must first identify Yin and Yang attributes.
Acute onset mostly belongs to Yang syndrome.
Chronic onset mostly belongs to Yin syndrome.
Diseases occurring in superficial skin and muscles belong to Yang.
Diseases occurring in deeper tendons and bones belong to Yin.
Red skin color in the pathological area belongs to Yang.
Purple-dark skin color in the pathological area belongs to Yin.
Elevated swelling belongs to Yang.
Flat or depressed swelling belongs to Yin.
Severe pain mostly belongs to Yang syndrome.
Dull pain, aching pain or spasmodic pain mostly belongs to Yin syndrome.
Thick yellow pus belongs to Yang.
Thin dark pus belongs to Yin.
Swelling is a pathological change caused by meridian obstruction and stagnation of Qi and blood.
Localized swelling is often seen in Yang syndromes and excess syndromes.
Diffuse swelling can be seen in both Yin and Yang syndromes.
Swelling caused by fire-heat often manifests as redness, swelling and burning pain.
Swelling caused by cold pathogen often manifests as pale skin color.
Swelling caused by wind pathogen often wanders from place to place.
Swelling caused by dampness pathogen is often marked by heaviness.
Swelling caused by phlegm pathogen often manifests as a mass.
Swelling caused by Qi stagnation often changes with emotional fluctuations.
Swelling caused by blood stasis is often accompanied by bluish-purple skin color.
Pain is caused by stagnation of Qi and blood and obstruction of the meridians.
Pain caused by fire-heat is often relieved by cold.
Pain caused by cold pathogen is often relieved by warmth.
Pain caused by wind pathogen often has no fixed location.
Pain caused by Qi stagnation is often closely related to emotions.
Pain caused by suppuration often presents as throbbing pain.
Pain caused by blood stasis is often manifested as stabbing pain.
Pruritus is caused by wind, dampness, heat or insects invading the skin surface.
Blood deficiency can also cause pruritus by depriving the skin of nourishment.
Pruritus caused by wind pathogen often wanders from place to place.
Pruritus caused by dampness pathogen is often accompanied by exudation.
Pruritus caused by heat pathogen is often accompanied by warm skin sensation.
Pus is a specific pathological product in surgical diseases.
Pus forms when excessive heat causes flesh to decay.
Discharge of pus reflects outward toxin expulsion by healthy Qi.
Differentiating pus helps judge the prognosis of surgical diseases.
Local burning heat and severe pain often indicate pus formation.
Gradual softening in the center of a mass often indicates pus formation.
Thick pus indicates that primordial Qi is relatively sufficient.
Thin and pale pus indicates that primordial Qi is relatively weak.
Yang-type ulcers are often covered with pus coating at the initial stage.
Persistent pus coating often indicates accumulation of pathogenic toxins.
Pale-red granulation often indicates insufficiency of Qi and blood.
Dry granulation with scanty fluid often indicates Yin deficiency.
Yin-type sores often show clear and thin pus at the initial stage.
Good signs indicate a healing tendency in surgical diseases.
Bad signs indicate deterioration of surgical diseases.
Emotional injury can lead to unsmooth Qi movement.
Unsmooth Qi movement can produce Qi stagnation, phlegm retention and blood stasis.
The dispersing method is used for Yang-type swollen sores before pus formation.
The expelling method promotes outward discharge of toxins by supporting healthy Qi.
Incision is used when pus has formed but cannot rupture spontaneously.
The pus-draining method promotes discharge of pus.
The slough-removing method clears necrotic tissue from the wound surface.
The granulation-promoting method promotes growth of new flesh.
The wound-closing method promotes healing of the ulcer opening.
